@(1.C.J.1 = 1-8) 
$ (1 line fragmentary)
…… far away …… the great gods. Lord @wDN{Enlil}, king of the lands, looked maliciously at @wGN{Sumer}. He demolished it. He destroyed the @wTN{Ki-ur}, the great place. He razed with the pickaxe all of the shining @wTN{E-kur}. He destroyed it but did not abandon it -- at the lunches, in his great dining hall, they call his name.

@(1.C.J.9 = 9-20) @wDN{Aruru}, the sister of @wDN{Enlil}, destroyed her city @wSN{Iri-saŋ-rig}. In @wSN{Keš}, the creation place of the Land, the people saw inside its holy sanctuary where daylight had been unknown. She destroyed it but did not abandon it -- at the lunches, in her great dining hall, they call her name. Lord @wDN{Nanna}, Lord @wDN{Ašimbabbar}, destroyed his city @wSN{Urim}. He decimated the Land with famine. He committed a sacrilege against the @wTN{E-kiš-nu-ŋal}. He struck at its heart. He destroyed it but did not abandon it -- at the lunches, in his great dining hall, they call his name.

@(1.C.J.21 = 21-25) @wDN{Inana}, the queen of heaven and earth, destroyed her city @wSN{Unug}. Fleeing from the @wTN{E-ana}, the house of seven corners and seven fires ……, she destroyed it but did not abandon it -- at the lunches, in her great dining hall, they call her name.

@(1.C.J.26 = 26) (@wDN{Damgalnuna} speaks:) @q[Damgalnuna,Enki]{“My beloved, who has ever seen such a destruction as that of your city @wSN{Eridug}!”}

