#lg L	kirugu


@(1.C.L.30 = 30-36) @q[Damgalnuna,Enki]{“Lord @wDN{Enki}, who has ever seen such a destruction as that of your city @wSN{Eridug}? Who has ever seen such a misfortune as that of the shrine @wTN{Abzu}, your house?”} No one goes up to his offering terrace. At the lunches, in his great dining hall, they do not call his name. @wDN{Enki}, king of the @fsux{abzu}, felt distressed, felt anxious. At the words of his spouse, he himself began to wail. He lay down and fasted.

@(1.C.L.37 = 37-44) My king, you must not be distressed, you must not be anxious. Father @wDN{Enki}, you must not be distressed, you must not be anxious. Son of @wDN{An}, return your heart to your @wTN{Ki-ur} and your attention to your city. Living in an alien city is miserable -- return your attention to your city. Living in an alien house is miserable -- return your attention to your house. What can anyone compare with this city? -- Return your attention to your city. What can anyone compare with this house? -- Return your attention to your house. @wSN{Eridug's} day is long. Its night is over.

@(1.C.L.45 = 45-52) May your throne say to you @q[throne,Enki]{“Sit down”}. May your bed say to you @q[bed,Enki]{“Lie down”}. May your house say to you @q[house,Enki]{“Be rested”}. May your holy dais also say joyfully to you @q[dais,Enki]{“Sit down”}. May your father @wDN{An}, the king of the gods, satisfy your heart. A person, a humble man, brings you a lament over your wife's faithful house. When he sings it before you, may that person soothe your heart. When he recites a prayer, look kindly upon him.

